# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dna
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Every mammalian cell seems to contain 5-Hydroxymethylcytosine, but the levels vary significantly depending on the cell type.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] The highest levels are found in neuronal cells of the central nervous system.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] The amount of hydroxymethylcytosine increases with age, as shown in mouse hippocampus and cerebellum.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] The exact function of this nitrogen base is still not fully elucidated, but it is thought that it may regulate gene expression or prompt DNA demethylation.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] This hypothesis is supported by the fact that artificial DNA that contains 5-hydroxymethylcytosines (5hmC) can be converted into unmodified cytosines once introduced into mammalian cells.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Moreover, 5hmC is highly enriched in primordial germ cells, where it apparently plays a role in global DNA demethylation.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] 5-Hydroxymethylcytosine may be especially important in the central nervous system, as it is found in very high levels there.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Reduction in the 5-Hydroxymethylcytosine levels have been found associated with impaired self-renewal in embryonic stem cells.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] 5-Hydroxymethylcytosine is also associated with labile, unstable nucleosomes which are frequently repositioned during cell differentiation.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] The accumulation of 5-hydroxymethylcytosine (5hmC) in post-mitotic neurons is associated with "functional demethylation" that facilitates transcription and gene expression.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] The term "demethylation," as applied to neurons, ordinarily refers to the replacement of 5-methylcytosine (5mC) by cytosine in DNA that can occur through a series of reactions involving a TET enzyme as well as enzymes of the DNA base excision repair pathway (see Epigenetics in learning and memory).
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] "Demethylation" of 5mC in DNA most often results in the promotion of expression of genes with neuronal activities.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Alterations in 5-hydroxymethylcytosine (5hmC) levels are implicated in a wide range of human diseases, with major roles identified in cancer biology, diagnostics, and neurodevelopmental disorders.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Aberrant 5hmC is widely reported in human disease, especially cancer.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Across many tumor types, global 5hmC is markedly reduced in malignant tissues compared with matched normal tissues, with diagnostic and prognostic implications.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] In melanoma, 5hmC is almost completely lost compared with benign nevi and normal melanocytes, and its depletion correlates with aggressive disease features.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] A systematic review and meta-analysis of 1,736 patients similarly found that negative/low 5hmC was associated with advanced stage and worse overall survival across cancers.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Loss of 5hmC is also frequent in hematologic malignancies such as peripheral T-cell lymphomas, irrespective of common mutations in epigenetic regulators.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Decreased 5hmC in cancer can reflect impaired ten-eleven translocation (TET) enzymes activity.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Mutant isocitrate dehydrogenase (IDH1/2) generates the oncometabolite 2-hydroxyglutarate, a competitive inhibitor of α-ketoglutarate-dependent dioxygenases that include TET enzymes, thereby reducing genomic 5hmC.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Down-regulation of IDH2/TET family members and restoration of 5hmC suppress tumor growth in melanoma, supporting a functional role for 5hmC loss in tumor progression.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Liquid-biopsy assays have leveraged 5hmC patterns in circulating cell-free DNA (cfDNA) for non-invasive cancer detection and stratification.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Genome-wide 5hmC profiling of cfDNA identified cancer-type-specific signatures that discriminated colorectal cancer and gastric cancer, among others, with high accuracy.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] In hepatocellular carcinoma, a 32-gene cfDNA 5hmC model showed superior performance to α-fetoprotein for early-stage detection in large validation cohorts.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] For pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma, integrating cfDNA 5mC with 5hmC further improved classification performance over either mark alone.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Beyond oncology, 5hmC has clinical relevance in the nervous system.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] MeCP2 - the protein mutated in Rett syndrome - binds 5hmC in brain chromatin, and a common Rett-causing MeCP2 mutation (R133C) preferentially disrupts 5hmC binding, supporting a role for 5hmC-mediated gene regulation in neurodevelopmental disease.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Phages probably evolved to use 5hmC to avoid recognition by most restriction enzymes in bacteria.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] The T4 phage uses 5hmC exclusively during replication, adding glycosylation to the hydroxyl group to further complicate the moiety.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Some bacteria have in turn evolved restriction enzymes specific for sites containing 5hmC.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] One prominent example is PvuRts1I, originally identified in 1994.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] 5hmC in T4 is produced by genome protein 42, deoxycytidylate 5-hydroxymethyltransferase (P08773; EC 2.1.2.8).
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] 5-Hydroxymethylcytosine was observed by Skirmantas Kriaucionis, an associate at the Heintz lab, who was looking for levels of 5-methylcytosine in two different neuron types.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] He discovered a significant amount of an unknown substance instead, and after conducting several tests, identified it as being 5-hydroxymethylcytosine.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Aravind used bioinformatic tools to predict that the Tet family of enzymes would likely oxidize 5-methylcytosine to 5-hydroxymethylcytosine.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] This was demonstrated in vitro and in live human and mouse cells by scientists working in the labs of Anjana Rao and David R.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] 5-Hydroxymethylcytosine was originally observed in mammals in 1972 by R.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Yura, but this initial finding is dubious.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Yura found 5-hmC present at extremely high levels in rat brain and liver, completely supplanting 5-methylcytosine.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] This contradicts all research conducted on mammalian DNA composition conducted before and since, including the Heintz and Rao papers, and another group was unable to reproduce Yura's result.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] With the discovery of 5-hydroxymethylcytosine some concerns have been raised regarding DNA methylation studies using the bisulfite sequencing technique.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] 5-hydroxymethylcytosine has been shown to behave like its precursor, 5-methylcytosine, in bisulfite conversion experiments.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] Therefore, bisulfite sequencing data may need to be revisited to verify whether the detected modified base is 5-methylcytosine or 5-hydroxymethylcytosine.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] In 2012 the lab of Chuan He discovered a method to solve the problems of 5-hydroxymethylcytosine being detected as 5-methylcytosine in normal bisulfite conversion experiments using the oxidative properties of the Tet-family of enzymes, this method has been termed TAB-seq.
[src:dna/5-hydroxymethylcytosine] In June 2020, Oxford Nanopore added a hydroxymethyl cytosine detection model to their research basecaller, rerio, allowing old signal-level data from any R9+ nanopore runs to be re-called to identify 5hmC.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] While trying to isolate the bacterial toxin responsible for tuberculosis, W.G.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Ruppel isolated a novel nucleic acid named tuberculinic acid in 1898 from *Tubercle bacillus*.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] The nucleic acid was found to be unusual, in that it contained in addition to thymine, guanine and cytosine, a methylated nucleotide.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] In 1925, Johnson and Coghill successfully detected a minor amount of a methylated cytosine derivative as a product of hydrolysis of tuberculinic acid with sulfuric acid.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] This report was severely criticized because their identification was based solely on the optical properties of the crystalline picrate, and other scientists failed to reproduce the same result.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] But its existence was ultimately proven in 1948, when Hotchkiss separated the nucleic acids of DNA from calf thymus using paper chromatography, by which he detected a unique methylated cytosine, quite distinct from conventional cytosine and uracil.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] After seven decades, it turned out that it is also a common feature in different RNA molecules, although the precise role is uncertain.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] While spontaneous deamination of cytosine forms uracil, which is recognized and removed by DNA repair enzymes, deamination of 5-methylcytosine forms thymine.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] This conversion of a DNA base from cytosine (C) to thymine (T) can result in a transition mutation.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] In addition, active enzymatic deamination of cytosine or 5-methylcytosine by the APOBEC family of cytosine deaminases could have beneficial implications on various cellular processes as well as on organismal evolution.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] The implications of deamination on 5-hydroxymethylcytosine, on the other hand, remains less understood.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] The NH2 group can be removed (deamination) from 5-methylcytosine to form thymine with use of reagents such as nitrous acid; cytosine deaminates to uracil (U) under similar conditions.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] 5-methylcytosine is resistant to deamination by bisulfite treatment, which deaminates cytosine residues.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] This property is often exploited to analyze DNA cytosine methylation patterns with bisulfite sequencing.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] 5mC marks are placed on genomic DNA via DNA methyltransferases (DNMTs).
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] There are 5 DNMTs in humans: DNMT1, DNMT2, DNMT3A, DNMT3B, and DNMT3L, and in algae and fungi 3 more are present (DNMT4, DNMT5, and DNMT6).
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] DNMT1 contains the replication foci targeting sequence (RFTS) and the CXXC domain which catalyze the addition of 5mC marks.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] RFTS directs DNMT1 to loci of DNA replication to assist in the maintenance of 5mC on daughter strands during DNA replication, whereas CXXC contains a zinc finger domain for *de novo* addition of methylation to the DNA.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] DNMT1 was found to be the predominant DNA methyltransferase in all human tissue.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Primarily, DNMT3A and DNMT3B are responsible for *de novo* methylation, and DNMT1 maintains the 5mC mark after replication.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] DNMTs can interact with each other to increase methylating capability.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] For example, 2 DNMT3L can form a complex with 2 DNMT3A to improve interactions with the DNA, facilitating the methylation.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Changes in the expression of DNMT results in aberrant methylation.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Overexpression produces increased methylation, whereas disruption of the enzyme decreased levels of methylation.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] The mechanism of the addition is as follows: first a cysteine residue on the DNMT's PCQ motif creates a nucleophillic attack at carbon 6 on the cytosine nucleotide that is to be methylated.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] S-Adenosylmethionine then donates a methyl group to carbon 5.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] A base in the DNMT enzyme deprotonates the residual hydrogen on carbon 5 restoring the double bond between carbon 5 and 6 in the ring, producing the 5-methylcytosine base pair.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] After a cytosine is methylated to 5mC, it can be reversed back to its initial state via multiple mechanisms.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Passive DNA demethylation by dilution eliminates the mark gradually through replication by a lack of maintenance by DNMT.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] In active DNA demethylation, a series of oxidations converts it to 5-hydroxymethylcytosine (5hmC), 5-formylcytosine (5fC), and 5-carboxylcytosine (5caC), and the latter two are eventually excised by thymine DNA glycosylase (TDG), followed by base excision repair (BER) to restore the cytosine.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] TDG knockout produced a 2-fold increase of 5fC without any statistically significant change to levels of 5hmC, indicating 5mC must be iteratively oxidized at least twice before its full demethylation.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] The oxidation occurs through the TET (Ten-eleven translocation) family dioxygenases (TET enzymes) which can convert 5mC, 5hmC, and 5fC to their oxidized forms.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] However, the enzyme has the greatest preference for 5mC and the initial reaction rate for 5hmC and 5fC conversions with TET2 are 4.9-7.6 fold slower.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] TET requires Fe(II) as cofactor, and oxygen and α-ketoglutarate (α-KG) as substrates, and the latter substrate is generated from isocitrate by the enzyme isocitrate dehydrogenase (IDH).
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Cancer however can produce 2-hydroxyglutarate (2HG) which competes with α-KG, reducing TET activity, and in turn reducing conversion of 5mC to 5hmC.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] In cancer, DNA can become both overly methylated, termed hypermethylation, and under-methylated, termed hypomethylation.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] CpG islands overlapping gene promoters are *de novo* methylated resulting in aberrant inactivation of genes normally associated with growth inhibition of tumors (an example of hypermethylation).
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Comparing tumor and normal tissue, the former had elevated levels of the methyltransferases DNMT1, DNMT3A, and mostly DNMT3B, all of which are associated with the abnormal levels of 5mC in cancer.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Repeat sequences in the genome, including satellite DNA, Alu, and long interspersed elements (LINE), are often seen hypomethylated in cancer, resulting in expression of these normally silenced genes, and levels are often significant markers of tumor progression.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] It has been hypothesized that there a connection between the hypermethylation and hypomethylation; over activity of DNA methyltransferases that produce the abnormal *de novo* 5mC methylation may be compensated by the removal of methylation, a type of epigenetic repair.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] However, the removal of methylation is inefficient resulting in an overshoot of genome-wide hypomethylation.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] The contrary may also be possible; over expression of hypomethylation may be silenced by genome-wide hypermethylation.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Cancer hallmark capabilities are likely acquired through epigenetic changes that alter the 5mC in both the cancer cells and in surrounding tumor-associated stroma within the tumor microenvironment.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] The anticancer drug Cisplatin has been reported to react with 5mC.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] "Epigenetic age" refers to the connection between chronological age and levels of DNA methylation in the genome.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Coupling the levels of DNA methylation, in specific sets of CpGs called "clock CpGs", with algorithms that regress the typical levels of collective genome-wide methylation at a given chronological age, allow for epigenetic age prediction.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] During youth (0–20 years old), changes in DNA methylation occur at a faster rate as development and growth progresses, and the changes begin to slow down at older ages.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Multiple epigenetic age estimators exist.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Horvath's clock measures a multi-tissue set of 353 CpGs, half of which positively correlate with age, and the other half negatively, to estimate the epigenetic age.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Hannum's clock utilizes adult blood samples to calculate age based on an orthogonal basis of 71 CpGs.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Levine's clock, known as DNAm PhenoAge, depends on 513 CpGs and surpasses the other age estimators in predicting mortality and lifespan, yet displays bias with non-blood tissues.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] There are reports of age estimators with the methylation state of only one CpG in the gene ELOVL2.
[src:dna/5-methylcytosine] Estimation of age allows for prediction lifespan through expectations of age related conditions that individuals may be subject to based on their 5mC methylation markers.
[src:dna/a-dna] Like the more common B-DNA, A-DNA is a right-handed double helix with major and minor grooves.
[src:dna/a-dna] However, as shown in the comparison table below, there is a slight increase in the number of base pairs (bp) per turn.
[src:dna/a-dna] This results in a smaller twist angle, and smaller rise per base pair, so that A-DNA is 20-25% shorter than B-DNA.
[src:dna/a-dna] The major groove of A-DNA is deep and narrow, while the minor groove is wide and shallow.
[src:dna/a-dna] A-DNA is broader and more compressed along its axis than B-DNA.
[src:dna/a-dna] The identifiable characteristic of A-DNA X-ray crystallography is the hole in the center.
[src:dna/a-dna] A-DNA has a C3'-endo pucker, which refers to the C3' carbon in the furanose ring being below the sugar plane.
[src:dna/a-dna] Research also indicates that A-form DNA can hybridize with the more common B-DNA.
[src:dna/a-dna] These A–B intermediate forms adopt the sugar pucker properties and/or the base conformation of both DNA forms.
[src:dna/a-dna] In one study, the characteristic C3'-endo pucker is found on the first three sugars of the DNA strand, while the last three sugars have a C2'-endo pucker, like B-DNA.
[src:dna/a-dna] These intermediates can form in aqueous solutions when the cytosine bases are methylated or brominated, altering the conformation.
[src:dna/a-dna] Alternatively, guanine and cytosine rich fragments have been shown to be easily converted from B to A-form in aqueous solutions.
[src:dna/a-dna] A-DNA can be derived from a few processes, including dehydration and protein binding.
[src:dna/a-dna] Dehydration of DNA drives it into the A form, which has been shown to protect DNA under conditions such as the extreme desiccation of bacteria.
[src:dna/a-dna] Protein binding can also strip solvent off of DNA and convert it to the A form, as revealed by the structure of several hyperthermophilic archaeal viruses.
[src:dna/a-dna] These viruses include rod-shaped rudiviruses SIRV2 and SSRV1, enveloped filamentous lipothrixviruses AFV1, SFV1 and SIFV, tristromavirus PFV2 as well as icosahedral portoglobovirus SPV1.
[src:dna/a-dna] A-form DNA is believed to be one of the adaptations of hyperthermophilic archaeal viruses to harsh environmental conditions in which these viruses thrive.
[src:dna/a-dna] It has been proposed that the motors that package double-stranded DNA in bacteriophages exploit the fact that A-DNA is shorter than B-DNA, and that conformational changes in the DNA itself are the source of the large forces generated by these motors.
[src:dna/a-dna] Experimental evidence for A-DNA as an intermediate in viral biomotor packing comes from double dye Förster resonance energy transfer measurements showing that B-DNA is shortened by 24% in a stalled ("crunched") A-form intermediate.
[src:dna/a-dna] In this model, ATP hydrolysis is used to drive protein conformational changes that alternatively dehydrate and rehydrate the DNA, and the DNA shortening/lengthening cycle is coupled to a protein-DNA grip/release cycle to generate the forward motion that moves DNA into the capsid.
[src:dna/acetylation] In chemistry, **acetylation** is an organic esterification reaction with acetic acid.
[src:dna/acetylation] It introduces an acetyl group into a chemical compound.
[src:dna/acetylation] Such compounds are termed *acetate esters* or simply *acetates*.
[src:dna/acetylation] **Deacetylation** is the opposite reaction, the removal of an acetyl group from a chemical compound.
[src:dna/acetylation] Histone deacetylases "play crucial roles in gene transcription and most likely in all eukaryotic biological processes that involve chromatin".
[src:dna/acetylation] Acetylation is one type of post-translational modification of proteins.
[src:dna/acetylation] The acetylation of the ε-amino group of lysine, which is common, converts a charged side chain to a neutral one.
[src:dna/acetylation] Acetylation/deacetylation of histones also plays a role in gene expression and cancer.
[src:dna/acetylation] These modifications are effected by enzymes called histone acetyltransferases (HATs) and histone deacetylases (HDACs).
[src:dna/acetylation] Two general mechanisms are known for deacetylation.
[src:dna/acetylation] One mechanism involves zinc binding to the acetyl oxygen.
[src:dna/acetylation] Another family of deacetylases require NAD+, which transfers an ribosyl group to the acetyl oxygen.
[src:dna/acetylation] Acetate esters and acetamides are generally prepared by acetylations.
[src:dna/acetylation] Acetylations are often used in making C-acetyl bonds in Friedel-Crafts reactions.
[src:dna/acetylation] Carbanions and their equivalents are susceptible to acetylations.
[src:dna/acetylation] Cellulose is a polyol and thus susceptible to acetylation, which is achieved using acetic anhydride.
[src:dna/acetylation] Acetylation disrupts hydrogen bonding, which otherwise dominates the properties of cellulose.
[src:dna/acetylation] Consequently, the cellulose esters are soluble in organic solvents and can be cast into fibers and films.
[src:dna/acetylation] Acetylation of wood is a chemical modification process that enhances the properties of wood by making it highly resistant to fungi and insects, as well as very durable against moisture and environmental parameters.
[src:dna/acetylation] The process involves the chemical reaction of acetic anhydride with the free hydroxyl groups in wood polymers, mostly of lignin and hemicelluloses, without requiring a catalyst.
[src:dna/acetylation] The modification results in bonds between the structural polymeric components, significantly reducing the ability of the -OH groups to form hydrogen bonds with water molecules.
[src:dna/acetylation] This effectively "locks" the cellular walls, minimizing the capacity of wood to absorb water and enhancing its dimensional stability.
[src:dna/acetylation] Approximately 80-90% of the hydroxyl groups of wood are modified during the process.
[src:dna/acetylation] The whole process is an environmentally friendly treatment, and has emerged, in the 21st century, as a significant innovation in the scientific area of wood science.
[src:dna/acetylation] Transacetylation uses vinyl acetate as an acetyl donor and lipase as a catalyst.
[src:dna/acetylation] This methodology allows the preparation of enantio-enriched alcohols and acetates.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:dna/acid-strength] A weak acid is only partially dissociated, or is partly ionized in water with both the undissociated acid and its dissociation products being present, in solution, in equilibrium with each other.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Acetic acid (CH3COOH) is an example of a weak acid.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The strength of a weak acid is quantified by its acid dissociation constant, $K_{a}$ value.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The strength of a weak organic acid may depend on substituent effects.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The strength of an inorganic acid is dependent on the oxidation state for the atom to which the proton may be attached.
[src:dna/acid-strength] For example, hydrogen chloride is a strong acid in aqueous solution, but is a weak acid when dissolved in glacial acetic acid.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The usual measure of the strength of an acid is its acid dissociation constant ( $K_{a}$ ), which can be determined experimentally by titration methods.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Stronger acids have a larger $K_{a}$ and a smaller logarithmic constant ( $\mathrm {p} K_{a}=-\log K_{a}$ ) than weaker acids.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H−A bond and the size of atom A, which determine the strength of the H−A bond.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Acid strengths also depend on the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Although these two concepts of acid strength often amount to the same general tendency of a substance to donate a proton, the $K_{a}$ and $H_{0}$ values are measures of distinct properties and may occasionally diverge.
[src:dna/acid-strength] For instance, hydrogen fluoride, whether dissolved in water ( $\mathrm {p} K_{a}=3.2$ ) or DMSO ( $\mathrm {p} K_{a}=15$ ), has $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ values indicating that it undergoes incomplete dissociation in these solvents, making it a weak acid.
[src:dna/acid-strength] However, as the rigorously dried, neat acidic medium, hydrogen fluoride has an $H_{0}$ value of –15, making it a more strongly protonating medium than 100% sulfuric acid and thus, by definition, a superacid.
[src:dna/acid-strength] (To prevent ambiguity, in the rest of this article, "strong acid" will, unless otherwise stated, refer to an acid that is strong as measured by its $\mathrm {p} K_{{\ce {a}}}$ value ( $\mathrm {p} K_{{\ce {a}}}<-1.74$ ).
[src:dna/acid-strength] When the acidic medium in question is a dilute aqueous solution, the $H_{0}$ is approximately equal to the pH value, which is a negative logarithm of the concentration of aqueous H+ in solution.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The pH of a simple solution of an acid in water is determined by both $K_{a}$ and the acid concentration.
[src:dna/acid-strength] For weak acid solutions, it depends on the degree of dissociation, which may be determined by an equilibrium calculation.
[src:dna/acid-strength] For concentrated solutions of acids, especially strong acids for which pH < 0, the $H_{0}$ value is a better measure of acidity than the pH.
[src:dna/acid-strength] where S represents a solvent molecule, such as a molecule of water or dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO), to such an extent that the concentration of the undissociated species HA is too low to be measured.
[src:dna/acid-strength] For practical purposes a strong acid can be said to be completely dissociated.
[src:dna/acid-strength] An example of a strong acid is perchloric acid.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Any acid with a $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ value which is less than about −2 behaves as a strong acid.
[src:dna/acid-strength] This results from the very high buffer capacity of solutions with a pH value of 1 or less and is known as the leveling effect.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The following are strong acids in aqueous and dimethyl sulfoxide solution.
[src:dna/acid-strength] As mentioned above, because the dissociation is so strongly favored, the concentrations of HA and thus the values of $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ cannot be measured experimentally.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The values in the following table are average values from as many as 8 different theoretical calculations.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Sulfonic acids, such as *p*-toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid) are a class of strong organic oxyacids.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Some sulfonic acids can be isolated as solids.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is an example of a substance that is a solid strong acid.
[src:dna/acid-strength] A weak acid is a substance that partially dissociates or partly ionizes when it is dissolved in a solvent.
[src:dna/acid-strength] In solution, there is an equilibrium between the acid, HA, and the products of dissociation.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The solvent (e.g. water) is omitted from this expression when its concentration is effectively unchanged by the process of acid dissociation.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Typical examples of weak acids include acetic acid and phosphorous acid.
[src:dna/acid-strength] An acid such as oxalic acid (HOOC−COOH) is said to be dibasic because it can lose two protons and react with two molecules of a simple base.
[src:dna/acid-strength] For a more rigorous treatment of acid strength see acid dissociation constant.
[src:dna/acid-strength] This includes acids such as the dibasic acid succinic acid, for which the simple method of calculating the pH of a solution, shown above, cannot be used.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The experimental determination of a $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ value is commonly performed by means of a titration.
[src:dna/acid-strength] A typical procedure would be as follows.
[src:dna/acid-strength] A quantity of strong acid is added to a solution containing the acid or a salt of the acid, to the point where the compound is fully protonated.
[src:dna/acid-strength] until only the deprotonated species, A−, remains in solution.
[src:dna/acid-strength] At each point in the titration pH is measured using a glass electrode and a pH meter.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The equilibrium constant is found by fitting calculated pH values to the observed values, using the method of least squares.
[src:dna/acid-strength] It is sometimes stated that "the conjugate of a weak acid is a strong base".
[src:dna/acid-strength] For example, acetic acid is a weak acid which has a $K_{a}=1.75\times 10^{-5}$ .
[src:dna/acid-strength] Its conjugate base is the acetate ion with $K_{b}=10^{-14}$ and $K_{a}=5.7\times 10^{-10}$ (from the relationship $K_{a}\times K_{b}=10^{-14}$ ), which certainly does not correspond to a strong base.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The conjugate of a weak acid is often a weak base and vice versa.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The strength of an acid varies from solvent to solvent.
[src:dna/acid-strength] An acid which is strong in water may be weak in a less basic solvent, and an acid which is weak in water may be strong in a more basic solvent.
[src:dna/acid-strength] According to Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory, the solvent S can accept a proton.
[src:dna/acid-strength] For example, hydrochloric acid is a weak acid in solution in pure acetic acid, HO2CCH3, which is less basic than water.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The extent of ionization of the hydrohalic acids decreases in the order HI > HBr > HCl.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Acetic acid is said to be a differentiating solvent for the three acids, while water is not.
[src:dna/acid-strength] An important example of a solvent which is more basic than water is dimethyl sulfoxide, DMSO, (CH3)2SO.
[src:dna/acid-strength] A compound which is a weak acid in water may become a strong acid in DMSO.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Acetic acid is an example of such a substance.
[src:dna/acid-strength] An extensive bibliography of $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ values in solution in DMSO and other solvents can be found at Acidity–Basicity Data in Nonaqueous Solvents.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Superacids are strong acids even in solvents of low dielectric constant.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid and magic acid.
[src:dna/acid-strength] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:dna/acid-strength] Lewis acids reacting with Lewis bases in gas phase and non-aqueous solvents have been classified in the ECW model, and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:dna/acid-strength] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:dna/acid-strength] For the qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for the quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:dna/acid-strength] In organic carboxylic acids, an electronegative substituent can pull electron density out of an acidic bond through the inductive effect, resulting in a smaller $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ value.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The effect decreases, the further the electronegative element is from the carboxylate group, as illustrated by the following series of halogenated butanoic acids.
[src:dna/acid-strength] In a set of oxoacids of an element, $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ values decrease with the oxidation state of the element.
[src:dna/acid-strength] The oxoacids of chlorine illustrate this trend.
[src:dna/acid] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:dna/acid] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:dna/acid] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:dna/acid] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:dna/acid] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:dna/acid] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:dna/acid] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:dna/acid] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:dna/acid] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:dna/acid] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:dna/acid] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:dna/acid] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:dna/acid] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:dna/acid] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:dna/acid] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:dna/acid] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:dna/acid] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:dna/acid] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:dna/acid] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:dna/acid] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:dna/acid] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:dna/acid] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:dna/acid] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:dna/acid] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:dna/acid] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:dna/acid] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:dna/acid] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:dna/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:dna/acid] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:dna/acid] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:dna/acid] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:dna/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:dna/acid] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:dna/acid] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:dna/acid] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:dna/acid] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:dna/acid] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:dna/acid] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:dna/acid] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:dna/acid] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:dna/acid] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:dna/acid] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:dna/acid] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:dna/acid] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:dna/acid] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:dna/acid] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:dna/acid] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:dna/acid] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:dna/acid] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:dna/acid] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:dna/acid] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:dna/acid] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:dna/acid] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:dna/acid] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:dna/acid] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:dna/acid] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:dna/acid] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:dna/acid] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:dna/acid] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:dna/acid] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:dna/acid] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:dna/acid] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:dna/acid] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:dna/acid] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:dna/acid] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:dna/acid] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:dna/acid] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:dna/acid] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:dna/acid] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:dna/acid] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:dna/acid] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:dna/acid] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:dna/acid] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:dna/acid] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:dna/acid] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:dna/acid] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:dna/acid] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:dna/acid] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:dna/acid] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:dna/acid] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:dna/acid] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:dna/acid] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:dna/acid] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:dna/acid] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:dna/acid] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:dna/acid] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:dna/acid] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:dna/acid] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:dna/acid] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:dna/acid] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:dna/acid] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:dna/acid] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:dna/acid] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:dna/acid] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:dna/acid] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:dna/acid] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:dna/acid] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:dna/acid] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:dna/acid] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:dna/acid] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:dna/acid] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:dna/acid] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:dna/acid] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:dna/acid] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:dna/acid] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:dna/acid] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:dna/acid] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:dna/acid] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:dna/acid] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:dna/acid] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:dna/acid] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:dna/acid] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:dna/acid] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:dna/acid] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:dna/acid] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:dna/acid] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:dna/acid] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:dna/acid] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:dna/acid] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:dna/acid] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:dna/acid] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:dna/acid] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:dna/acid] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:dna/acid] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:dna/acid] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:dna/acid] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:dna/acid] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:dna/acid] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:dna/acid] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:dna/acid] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:dna/acid] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:dna/acid] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:dna/acid] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:dna/acid] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:dna/acid] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:dna/acid] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:dna/acid] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:dna/acid] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:dna/acid] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:dna/acid] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:dna/acid] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:dna/acid] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:dna/acid] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:dna/acid] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:dna/acid] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:dna/acid] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:dna/acid] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:dna/acid] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:dna/acid] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:dna/acid] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:dna/acid] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:dna/acid] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:dna/acid] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:dna/acid] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:dna/acid] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:dna/acid] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:dna/acid] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:dna/acid] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:dna/acid] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:dna/acid] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:dna/acid] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:dna/acid] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:dna/acid] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:dna/acid] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:dna/acid] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:dna/acid] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:dna/acid] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:dna/acid] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:dna/acid] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:dna/acid] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:dna/acid] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:dna/acid] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:dna/acid] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:dna/acid] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:dna/acid] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:dna/acid] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:dna/acid] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:dna/acid] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:dna/acid] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:dna/acid] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:dna/acid] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:dna/acid] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:dna/acid] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:dna/acid] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:dna/acid] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:dna/acid] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:dna/acid] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:dna/acid] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:dna/acid] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:dna/acid] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:dna/acid] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:dna/acid] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:dna/acid] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:dna/acid] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:dna/acid] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:dna/acid] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:dna/acid] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:dna/acid] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:dna/acid] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:dna/acid] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:dna/acid] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:dna/acid] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:dna/acid] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:dna/acid] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:dna/acid] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:dna/acid] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:dna/acid] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:dna/acid] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:dna/acid] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:dna/acid] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:dna/acid] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:dna/acid] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:dna/acid] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:dna/acid] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:dna/acid] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:dna/acid] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:dna/acid] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:dna/acid] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:dna/acid] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:dna/acid] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:dna/acid] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:dna/acid] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:dna/acid] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:dna/acid] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:dna/acid] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:dna/acid] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:dna/ap-news] The **Associated Press** (**AP**) is an American not-for-profit news agency headquartered in New York City.
[src:dna/ap-news] Founded in 1846, it operates as a cooperative, unincorporated association, and produces news reports that are distributed to its members, major U.S. daily newspapers and radio and television broadcasters.
[src:dna/ap-news] Since the Pulitzer Prize was established in 1917, the AP has earned 60 of them, including 36 for photography.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP distributes its widely used *AP Stylebook*, its AP polls tracking NCAA sports, and its election polls and results during U.S. elections.
[src:dna/ap-news] It sponsors the National Football League's annual awards.
[src:dna/ap-news] By 2016, news collected by the AP was published and republished by more than 1,300 newspapers and broadcasters.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP operates 235 news bureaus in 94 countries, and publishes in English, Spanish, and Arabic.
[src:dna/ap-news] It also operates the AP Radio Network, which provides twice hourly newscasts and daily sportscasts for broadcast and satellite radio and television stations.
[src:dna/ap-news] Many newspapers and broadcasters outside the United States are AP subscribers, paying a fee to use AP material without being contributing members of the cooperative.
[src:dna/ap-news] As part of their cooperative agreement with the AP, most member news organizations grant automatic permission for the AP to distribute their local news reports.
[src:dna/ap-news] As of 2025, the AP attracts more than 128 million monthly website visits, making it one of the top 10 news websites in the U.S.
[src:dna/ap-news] The Associated Press was formed in May 1846 by five daily newspapers in New York City to share the cost of transmitting news of the Mexican–American War.
[src:dna/ap-news] The venture was organized by Moses Yale Beach (1800–68), second publisher of *The Sun*, joined by the *New York Herald*, the *New York Courier and Enquirer*, *The Journal of Commerce*, and the *New York Evening Express*.
[src:dna/ap-news] Some historians believe that the *New-York Tribune* joined at this time; documents show it was a member in 1849.
[src:dna/ap-news] *The New York Times* became a member in September 1851.
[src:dna/ap-news] Initially known as the New York Associated Press (NYAP), the organization faced competition from the Western Associated Press (1862), which criticized its monopolistic news gathering and price setting practices.
[src:dna/ap-news] An investigation completed in 1892 by Victor Lawson, editor and publisher of the *Chicago Daily News*, revealed that several principals of the NYAP entered into a secret agreement with United Press, a rival organization, to share NYAP news and the profits of reselling it.
[src:dna/ap-news] The findings led to the dissolving of the NYAP.
[src:dna/ap-news] That December, the Western Associated Press was incorporated in Illinois as the Associated Press.
[src:dna/ap-news] A 1900 Illinois Supreme Court decision (*Inter Ocean Publishing Co. v.
[src:dna/ap-news] Associated Press*) holding that the AP was a public utility and operating in restraint of trade resulted in the AP's move from Chicago to New York City, where corporation laws were more favorable to cooperatives.
[src:dna/ap-news] In 1935, the AP launched the Wirephoto network, which allowed transmission of news photographs over leased private telephone lines on the day they were taken.
[src:dna/ap-news] This gave the AP a major advantage over other news media outlets.
[src:dna/ap-news] While the first network was only between New York, Chicago, and San Francisco, eventually the AP had its network across the whole United States.
[src:dna/ap-news] In 1945, the Supreme Court of the United States held in *Associated Press v.
[src:dna/ap-news] United States* that the AP had been violating the Sherman Antitrust Act by prohibiting member newspapers from selling or providing news to nonmember organizations as well as making it very difficult for nonmember newspapers to join the AP.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP entered the broadcast field in 1941 when it began distributing news to radio stations; it created its own radio network in 1974.
[src:dna/ap-news] In 1994, it established APTV, a global video newsgathering agency.
[src:dna/ap-news] APTV merged with Worldwide Television News in 1998 to form APTN, which provides video to international broadcasters and websites.
[src:dna/ap-news] In 2004, the AP moved its headquarters from its long-time home at 50 Rockefeller Plaza to 450 West 33rd Street in Manhattan.
[src:dna/ap-news] In 2019, AP had more than 240 bureaus globally.
[src:dna/ap-news] Its mission has not changed since its founding, but digital technology has made the distribution of the AP news report an interactive endeavor between the AP and its hundreds of U.S. newspaper members, as well as broadcasters, international subscribers, and online customers.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP began diversifying its news gathering capabilities.
[src:dna/ap-news] By 2007, the AP was generating only about 30% of its revenue from United States newspapers, and by 2024, this had declined to 10%.
[src:dna/ap-news] 37% came from the global broadcast customers, 15% from online ventures and 18% came from international newspapers and from photography.
[src:dna/ap-news] In March 2024, Gannett, the largest U.S. newspaper publisher as measured by total daily circulation, announced that effective March 25, 2024, it would no longer use content from the AP.
[src:dna/ap-news] A spokesperson for AP said that they were "shocked and disappointed" by this development.
[src:dna/ap-news] Newspaper chain McClatchy announced that it would also stop using some AP services.
[src:dna/ap-news] Gannett and McClatchy will both continue to use AP's election results data.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP's multi-topic structure has resulted in web portals such as Yahoo! and MSN posting its articles, often relying on the AP as their first source for news coverage of breaking news items.
[src:dna/ap-news] This and the constant updating evolving stories require has had a major impact on the AP's public image and role, giving new credence to the AP's ongoing mission of having staff for covering every area of news fully and promptly.
[src:dna/ap-news] In 2007, Google announced that it was paying to receive AP content, to be displayed in Google News, interrupted from late 2009 to mid-2010 due to a licensing dispute.
[src:dna/ap-news] A 2017 study by NewsWhip revealed that AP content was more engaged with on Facebook than content from any individual English-language publisher.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP is governed by an elected board of directors.
[src:dna/ap-news] Since 2022, the board's chairperson is Gracia C.
[src:dna/ap-news] Martore, former president and CEO of Tegna, Inc.
[src:dna/ap-news] AP reports from countries where press freedom is restricted, sometimes under adverse circumstances, and operates out of more than 100 regional offices.
[src:dna/ap-news] In 2025, restrictions preventing AP reporting in the U.S. were imposed by the second Trump administration.
[src:dna/ap-news] In February 2025, two AP reporters were barred from covering several events at the White House, because of the AP refusal to refer to the Gulf of Mexico as the "Gulf of America", as directed by the White House.
[src:dna/ap-news] The restrictions against AP were extended to other reporting opportunities such as in Air Force One.
[src:dna/ap-news] On February 21, 2025, the AP sued the Trump administration in *Associated Press v.
[src:dna/ap-news] Budowich* for blocking their attendance.
[src:dna/ap-news] On February 24, 2025, a federal judge declined to issue an immediate order compelling the White House to reinstate access to presidential events to AP, although he encouraged the White House to do so.
[src:dna/ap-news] On April 8, 2025, Judge Trevor McFadden ruled that the White House must lift the access restrictions they placed on the AP while the *AP v.
[src:dna/ap-news] On June 6, 2025, the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit imposed a stay upon the lower court's order, allowing the White House to resume barring access to some media events.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP is one of two organizations that collect and verify election results in every city and county across the United States, including races for the U.S. president, the Senate and House of Representatives, and governors as well as other statewide offices.
[src:dna/ap-news] Known for accuracy, the organization has collected and published presidential election data since 1848.
[src:dna/ap-news] Major news outlets rely on the polling data and results provided by the Associated Press before declaring a winner in major political races, particularly the presidential election.
[src:dna/ap-news] In declaring the winners, the AP has historically relied on a robust network of local reporters with first-hand knowledge of assigned territories who also have long-standing relationships with county clerks as well as other local officials.
[src:dna/ap-news] Moreover, the AP monitors and gathers data from county websites and electronic feeds provided by states.
[src:dna/ap-news] The research team further verifies the results by considering demographics, number of absentee ballots, and other political issues that may have an effect on the final results.
[src:dna/ap-news] In 2018, the AP introduced a new system called AP VoteCast, which was developed together with NORC at the University of Chicago in order to further improve the reliability of its data and overcome biases of its legacy exit poll.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP conducts polls for numerous college sports in the United States.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP college football rankings were created in 1936, and began including the top 25 teams in 1989.
[src:dna/ap-news] Since 1969, the final poll of each season has been released after all bowl games have been played.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP released its all-time Top 25 in 2016.
[src:dna/ap-news] As of 2017, 22 different programs had finished in the number one spot of the poll since its inception.
[src:dna/ap-news] In the pre-bowl game determination era, the AP poll was often used as the distinction for a national champion in football.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP college basketball poll has been used as a guide for which teams deserve national attention.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP first began its poll of college basketball teams in 1949, and has since conducted over 1,100 polls.
[src:dna/ap-news] The college basketball poll started with 20 teams and was reduced to 10 during the 1960–61 college basketball season.
[src:dna/ap-news] It returned to 20 teams in 1968–69 and expanded to 25 beginning in 1989–90.
[src:dna/ap-news] The final poll for each season is released prior to the conclusion of the NCAA tournament, so all data includes regular season games only.
[src:dna/ap-news] In 2017, The AP released a list of the Top 100 teams of all time.
[src:dna/ap-news] The poll counted poll appearances (one point) and No.
[src:dna/ap-news] 1 rankings (two points) to rank each team.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP began its Major League Baseball Manager of the Year Award in 1959, for a manager in each league.
[src:dna/ap-news] From 1984 to 2000, the award was given to one manager in all of MLB.
[src:dna/ap-news] The winners were chosen by a national panel of AP baseball writers and radio men.
[src:dna/ap-news] Every year, the AP releases the names of the winners of its AP College Basketball Player of the Year and AP College Basketball Coach of the Year awards.
[src:dna/ap-news] It also honors a group of All-American players.
[src:dna/ap-news] In 1994, London-based Associated Press Television (APTV) was founded to provide agency news material to television broadcasters.
[src:dna/ap-news] In 1998, the AP purchased Worldwide Television News (WTN) from the ABC News division of The Walt Disney Company, Nine Network Australia and ITN London.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP publishes 70,000 videos and 6,000 hours of live video per year, as of 2016.
[src:dna/ap-news] The agency also provides seven simultaneous live video channels, AP Direct for broadcasters, and six live channels on AP Live Choice for broadcasters and digital publishers.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP was the first news agency to launch a live video news service in 2003.
[src:dna/ap-news] The first publicly available edition of the book was published in 1953.
[src:dna/ap-news] The first modern edition was published in August 1977 by Lorenz Press.
[src:dna/ap-news] Afterwards, various paperback editions were published by different publishers, including, among others, Turtleback Books, Penguin's Laurel Press, Pearson's Addison-Wesley, and Hachette's Perseus Books and Basic Books.
[src:dna/ap-news] Recent editions are released in several formats, including paperback and flat-lying spiral-bound editions, as well as a digital e-book edition and an online subscription version.
[src:dna/ap-news] Additionally, the *AP Stylebook* also provides English grammar recommendations through social media, including Twitter, Facebook, Pinterest, and Instagram.
[src:dna/ap-news] From 1977 to 2005, more than two million copies of the *AP Stylebook* were sold worldwide, with that number climbing to 2.5 million by 2011.
[src:dna/ap-news] Writers in broadcasting, news, magazine publishing, marketing departments, and public relations firms traditionally adopt and apply AP grammar and punctuation styles.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP collaborated with Nazi Germany and gave it access to its photographic archives for its antisemitic Nazi propaganda.
[src:dna/ap-news] AP also cooperated with the Nazi regime through censorship.
[src:dna/ap-news] In 2017, the German historian Norman Domeier of the University of Vienna brought to wider attention the deal between the AP and the Nazi government related to the interchange of press photos during the period in which the United States was at war with Nazi Germany.
[src:dna/ap-news] This relationship involved the Bureau Laux, run by the Waffen-SS photographer Helmut Laux.
[src:dna/ap-news] The mechanism for this interchange involved a courier flying to Lisbon and back each day transporting photos from and for Nazi Germany's wartime enemy, the United States, via diplomatic pouch.
[src:dna/ap-news] The transactions were initially conducted at the AP bureau under Luiz Lupi in Lisbon, and from 1944, when the exchange via Lisbon took too long, also at the AP bureau in Stockholm under Eddie Shanke.
[src:dna/ap-news] Here, as a cover, the Swedish agency, Pressens Bild, was involved as an intermediary.
[src:dna/ap-news] An estimated 40,000 photos were exchanged between the enemies in this way.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP was kicked out of Nazi Germany when the United States entered World War II in December 1941.
[src:dna/ap-news] Israeli journalist Matti Friedman accused the AP of killing a story he wrote about the "war of words", "between Israel and its critics in human rights organizations", in the aftermath of the 2008–2009 Gaza war.
[src:dna/ap-news] On September 29, 2000, the first day of the Second Intifada, the AP published a photograph of a badly-bloodied young man behind whom a police officer could be seen with a baton raised in a menacing fashion; a gas station with Hebrew lettering could also be seen in the background.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP labelled it with the caption "An Israeli policeman and a Palestinian on the Temple Mount", and the picture and caption were subsequently published in several major American newspapers, including the *New York Times*.
[src:dna/ap-news] In reality, the injured man in the photograph was a Jewish yeshiva student from Chicago named Tuvia Grossman, and the police officer, a Druze named Gidon Tzefadi, was protecting Grossman from a Palestinian mob who had clubbed, stoned, and stabbed Grossman.
[src:dna/ap-news] There are also no gas stations with Hebrew lettering on the Temple Mount.
[src:dna/ap-news] The episode is often cited by those who accuse the media of having an anti-Israel bias, and was the impetus for the founding of the pro-Israel group HonestReporting.
[src:dna/ap-news] After a letter from Grossman's father noted the error, the AP, the *New York Times*, and other papers published corrections; despite these corrections, the photograph continues to be used by critics of Israel as a symbol of Israeli aggression and violence.
[src:dna/ap-news] During the 2021 Israel–Palestine crisis, the Israeli army destroyed the al-Jalaa Highrise, a building housing the AP's Gaza offices and Al Jazeera offices.
[src:dna/ap-news] Israel stated that the building housed Hamas military intelligence and had given advanced warning of the strike, and no civilians were harmed.
[src:dna/ap-news] AP CEO Gary Pruitt released a statement on May 16, stating that he "had no indication Hamas was in the building" and called on the Israeli government to provide the evidence.
[src:dna/ap-news] On May 17, US secretary of state Antony Blinken said he had not seen any evidence that Hamas operated from the building housing the AP and Al Jazeera, but it is the job of others to handle intelligence matters.
[src:dna/ap-news] Israel reportedly shared intelligence with American officials and U.S. president Joe Biden showing Hamas offices inside the building.
[src:dna/ap-news] Reporters Without Borders asked the International Criminal Court to investigate the bombing as a possible war crime.
[src:dna/ap-news] On June 8, the Israeli ambassador to the US, Gilad Erdan, met with AP CEO Gary Pruitt and vice president for foreign news, Ian Phillips, to discuss the operation.
[src:dna/ap-news] In coordination with the IDF, Erdan said the site was used by Hamas intelligence officials to develop and carry out electronic warfare operations, and that IDF did not suspect the AP was aware of the alleged covert Hamas presence.
[src:dna/ap-news] After the meeting the AP stated "We have yet to receive evidence to support these claims".
[src:dna/ap-news] In May 2024, Israeli officials seized equipment broadcasting a live stream of Northern Gaza from the town of Sderot as part of a ban on Al Jazeera Media in Israel which had received footage from the broadcast.
[src:dna/ap-news] The move was condemned by multiple journalism organizations, Israeli opposition politicians, and US government officials.
[src:dna/ap-news] In 1994, Tina Susman was on her fourth trip to Somalia, reporting for the AP.
[src:dna/ap-news] She was reporting on U.S. peacekeeping troops leaving the country.
[src:dna/ap-news] Somali rebels outnumbered her bodyguards in Mogadishu, dragged her from her car in broad daylight, and held her for 20 days.
[src:dna/ap-news] She told *The Quill* that she believes being a woman was an advantage in her experience there.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP had requested news organizations including *The New York Times*, the *Chicago Tribune,* and *The Washington Post* to suppress the story to discourage the emboldening of the kidnappers.
[src:dna/ap-news] In September 2002, Washington, D.C. bureau reporter Christopher Newton, an AP reporter since 1994, was fired after he was accused of fabricating sources since 2000, including at least 40 people and organizations.
[src:dna/ap-news] Prior to his firing, Newton had been focused on writing about federal law enforcement while based at the Justice Department.
[src:dna/ap-news] Some of the nonexistent agencies quoted in his stories included "Education Alliance", the "Institute for Crime and Punishment in Chicago", "Voice for the Disabled", and "People for Civil Rights".
[src:dna/ap-news] In 2007, an FBI agent working in Seattle impersonated an AP journalist and infected the computer of a 15-year-old suspect with malicious surveillance software.
[src:dna/ap-news] The incident sparked a strongly worded statement from the AP demanding that the bureau never impersonate a member of the news media again.
[src:dna/ap-news] In September 2016, the incident resulted in a report by the Justice Department, which the AP said "effectively condone[d] the FBI's impersonation".
[src:dna/ap-news] In December 2017, following a US court appearance, a judge ruled in favor of the AP in a lawsuit against the FBI for fraudulently impersonating a member of the news media in conjunction with the 2007 case.
[src:dna/ap-news] In June 2008, the AP sent numerous DMCA take-down demands and threatened legal action against several blogs.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP contended that the internet blogs were violating the AP's copyright by linking to AP material and using headlines and short summaries in those links.
[src:dna/ap-news] Many bloggers and experts noted that the use of the AP news fell squarely under commonly accepted internet practices and within fair-use standards.
[src:dna/ap-news] Others noted and demonstrated that the AP routinely takes similar excerpts from other sources, often without attribution or licenses.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP responded that it was defining standards regarding citations of AP news.
[src:dna/ap-news] In March 2009, the AP counter-sued artist Shepard Fairey over his famous image of Barack Obama, saying the uncredited, uncompensated use of an AP photo violated copyright laws and signaled a threat to journalism.
[src:dna/ap-news] Fairey had sued the AP the previous month over his artwork, titled "Obama Hope" and "Obama Progress", arguing that he did not violate copyright law because he dramatically changed the image.
[src:dna/ap-news] The artwork, based on an April 2006 picture taken for the AP by Mannie Garcia, was a popular image during the 2008 presidential election and now hangs in the National Portrait Gallery in Washington, D.C.
[src:dna/ap-news] According to the AP's lawsuit filed in federal court in Manhattan, Fairey knowingly "misappropriated The AP's rights in that image".
[src:dna/ap-news] The suit asked the court to award the AP profits made off the image and damages.
[src:dna/ap-news] Fairey said he looked forward to "upholding the free expression rights at stake here" and disproving the AP's accusations.
[src:dna/ap-news] In January 2011, the suit was settled with neither side declaring their position to be wrong but agreeing to share reproduction rights and profits from Fairey's work.
[src:dna/ap-news] In January 2008, the AP sued competitor All Headline News (AHN) claiming that AHN allegedly infringed on its copyrights and a contentious "quasi-property" right to facts.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP complaint asserted that AHN reporters had copied facts from AP news reports without permission and without paying a syndication fee.
[src:dna/ap-news] After AHN moved to dismiss all but the copyright claims set forth by the AP, a majority of the lawsuit was dismissed.
[src:dna/ap-news] The case has been dismissed and both parties settled.
[src:dna/ap-news] On April 23, 2013, hackers posted a tweet to AP's Twitter account about fictional attacks on the White House, falsely claiming that President Obama had been injured.
[src:dna/ap-news] The hoax caused a flash crash on the American stock markets, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average briefly falling by 143 points.
[src:dna/ap-news] On May 13, 2013, the AP announced that telephone records for 20 of their reporters during a two-month period in 2012 had been subpoenaed by the U.S.
[src:dna/ap-news] Justice Department and described these acts as a "massive and unprecedented intrusion" into news-gathering operations.
[src:dna/ap-news] The DOJ did not direct subpoenas to the AP, instead going to their phone providers, including Verizon Wireless.
[src:dna/ap-news] Attorney General Eric Holder testified under oath in front of the House Judiciary Committee that he recused himself from the leak investigations to avoid any appearance of a conflict of interest.
[src:dna/ap-news] Holder said his Deputy Attorney General, James M.
[src:dna/ap-news] Cole, was in charge of the AP investigation and would have ordered the subpoenas.
[src:dna/ap-news] On January 10, 2022, AP announced it would start selling non-fungible tokens (NFTs) of their photographs in partnership with a company named Xooa, with the proceeds being used to fund their operations.
[src:dna/ap-news] One of the NFTs they promoted on Twitter on 24 February was an aerial shot depicting an overcrowded migrant boat in the Mediterranean Sea by Brazilian photojournalist Felipe Dana.
[src:dna/ap-news] The sale received negative backlash from users and other journalists, with AP being accused of profiting off of human suffering and the picture choice being "dystopian" and "in extremely poor taste".
[src:dna/ap-news] The tweet was subsequently deleted and the NFT, which was to be sold the next day, was pulled from market.
[src:dna/ap-news] Global director of media relations Lauren Easton apologized, saying "This was a poor choice of imagery for an NFT.
[src:dna/ap-news] It has not and will not be put up for auction ...
[src:dna/ap-news] AP's NFT marketplace is a very early pilot program, and we are immediately reviewing our efforts".
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP has earned 59 Pulitzer Prizes, including 36 for photography, since the award was established in 1917.
[src:dna/ap-news] In May 2020, Dar Yasin, Mukhtar Khan, and Channi Anand of the AP were honored with the 2020 Pulitzer Prize for Feature Photography.
[src:dna/ap-news] The choice caused controversy, because it was taken by some as questioning "India's legitimacy over Kashmir" as it had used the word "independence" in regard to revocation of Article 370.
[src:dna/ap-news] The AP won an Oscar in 2024 for the documentary film *20 Days in Mariupol*, a first-person account of the early days of Russia's invasion of Ukraine in 2022.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The two DNA strands are known as polynucleotides as they are composed of simpler monomeric units called nucleotides.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Each nucleotide is composed of one of four nitrogen-containing nucleobases (cytosine [C], guanine [G], adenine [A] or thymine [T]), a sugar called deoxyribose, and a phosphate group.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The nucleotides are joined to one another in a chain by covalent bonds (known as the phosphodiester linkage) between the sugar of one nucleotide and the phosphate of the next, resulting in an alternating sugar-phosphate backbone.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The nitrogenous bases of the two separate polynucleotide strands are bound together, according to base pairing rules (A with T and C with G), with hydrogen bonds to make double-stranded DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The complementary nitrogenous bases are divided into two groups, the single-ringed pyrimidines and the double-ringed purines.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In DNA, the pyrimidines are thymine and cytosine; the purines are adenine and guanine.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Both strands of double-stranded DNA store the same biological information.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This information is replicated when the two strands separate.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The two strands of DNA run in opposite directions to each other and are thus antiparallel.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Attached to each sugar is one of four types of nucleobases (or *bases*).
[src:dna/dna-p01] It is the sequence of these four nucleobases along the backbone that encodes genetic information.
[src:dna/dna-p01] RNA strands are created using DNA strands as a template in a process called transcription, where DNA bases are exchanged for their corresponding bases except in the case of thymine (T), for which RNA substitutes uracil (U).
[src:dna/dna-p01] Under the genetic code, these RNA strands specify the sequence of amino acids within proteins in a process called translation.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Within eukaryotic cells, DNA is organized into long structures called chromosomes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Before typical cell division, these chromosomes are duplicated in the process of DNA replication, providing a complete set of chromosomes for each daughter cell.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Eukaryotic organisms (animals, plants, fungi and protists) store most of their DNA inside the cell nucleus as nuclear DNA, and some in the mitochondria as mitochondrial DNA or in chloroplasts as chloroplast DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In contrast, prokaryotes (bacteria and archaea) store their DNA only in the cytoplasm, in circular chromosomes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Within eukaryotic chromosomes, chromatin proteins, such as histones, compact and organize DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These compacting structures guide the interactions between DNA and other proteins, helping control which parts of the DNA are transcribed.
[src:dna/dna-p01] DNA is a long polymer made from repeating units called nucleotides.
[src:dna/dna-p01] DNA does not usually exist as a single strand, but instead as a pair of strands that are held tightly together.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These two long strands coil around each other, in the shape of a double helix.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The nucleotide contains both a segment of the backbone of the molecule (which holds the chain together) and a nucleobase (which interacts with the other DNA strand in the helix).
[src:dna/dna-p01] A nucleobase linked to a sugar is called a nucleoside, and a base linked to a sugar and to one or more phosphate groups is called a nucleotide.
[src:dna/dna-p01] A biopolymer comprising multiple linked nucleotides (as in DNA) is called a polynucleotide.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The structure of DNA is dynamic along its length, being capable of coiling into tight loops and other shapes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In all species it is composed of two helical chains, bound to each other by hydrogen bonds.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The two chains are coiled around the same axis (but not directly opposite one to the other), and have the same pitch of 34 ångströms (3.4 nm).
[src:dna/dna-p01] Ignoring the identities of the bases, the line group is D1(q), where q stands for the turn per base pair, which is around a tenth of a full turn.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In the usual form (B-DNA), the twist is right-handed, like a normal screw that advances when turned clockwise.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The pair of chains have a radius of 10 Å (1.0 nm).
[src:dna/dna-p01] According to another study, when measured in a different solution, the DNA chain measured 22–26 Å (2.2–2.6 nm) wide, and one nucleotide unit measured 3.3 Å (0.33 nm) long.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The buoyant density of most DNA is 1.7g/cm3.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The backbone of the DNA strand is made from alternating phosphate and sugar groups.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The sugar in DNA is 2-deoxyribose, which is a pentose (five-carbon) sugar.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The sugars are joined by phosphate groups that form phosphodiester bonds between the third and fifth carbon atoms of adjacent sugar rings.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These are known as the 3′-end (three prime end), and 5′-end (five prime end) carbons, the prime symbol being used to distinguish these carbon atoms from those of the base to which the deoxyribose forms a glycosidic bond.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Therefore, any DNA strand normally has one end at which there is a phosphate group attached to the 5′ carbon of a ribose (the 5′ phosphoryl) and another end at which there is a free hydroxyl group attached to the 3′ carbon of a ribose (the 3′ hydroxyl).
[src:dna/dna-p01] The orientation of the 3′ and 5′ carbons along the sugar-phosphate backbone confers directionality (sometimes called polarity) to each DNA strand.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In a nucleic acid double helix, the direction of the nucleotides in one strand is opposite to their direction in the other strand: the strands are antiparallel.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The asymmetric ends of DNA strands are said to have a directionality of five prime end (5′ ), and three prime end (3′), with the 5′ end having a terminal phosphate group and the 3′ end a terminal hydroxyl group.
[src:dna/dna-p01] One major difference between DNA and RNA is the sugar, with the 2-deoxyribose in DNA being replaced by the related pentose sugar ribose in RNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The DNA double helix is stabilized primarily by two forces: hydrogen bonds between nucleotides and base-stacking interactions among aromatic nucleobases.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The four bases found in DNA are adenine (A), cytosine (C), guanine (G) and thymine (T).
[src:dna/dna-p01] These four bases are attached to the sugar-phosphate to form the complete nucleotide, as shown for adenosine monophosphate.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Adenine pairs with thymine and guanine pairs with cytosine, forming A-T and G-C base pairs.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The nucleobases are classified into two types: the purines, A and G, which are fused five- and six-membered heterocyclic compounds, and the pyrimidines, the six-membered rings C and T.
[src:dna/dna-p01] A fifth pyrimidine nucleobase, uracil (U), usually takes the place of thymine in RNA and differs from thymine by lacking a methyl group on its ring.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In addition to RNA and DNA, many artificial nucleic acid analogues have been created to study the properties of nucleic acids, or for use in biotechnology.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The first of these recognized was 5-methylcytosine, which was found in the genome of *Mycobacterium tuberculosis* in 1925.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The reason for the presence of these noncanonical bases in bacterial viruses (bacteriophages) is to avoid the restriction enzymes present in bacteria.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This enzyme system acts at least in part as a molecular immune system protecting bacteria from infection by viruses.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Modifications of the bases cytosine and adenine, the more common and modified DNA bases, play vital roles in the epigenetic control of gene expression in plants and animals.
[src:dna/dna-p01] A number of noncanonical bases are known to occur in DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Most of these are modifications of the canonical bases plus uracil.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Twin helical strands form the DNA backbone.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Another double helix may be found tracing the spaces, or grooves, between the strands.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These voids are adjacent to the base pairs and may provide a binding site.
[src:dna/dna-p01] As the strands are not symmetrically located with respect to each other, the grooves are unequally sized.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The major groove is 22 ångströms (2.2 nm) wide, while the minor groove is 12 Å (1.2 nm) in width.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Due to the larger width of the major groove, the edges of the bases are more accessible in the major groove than in the minor groove.
[src:dna/dna-p01] As a result, proteins such as transcription factors that can bind to specific sequences in double-stranded DNA usually make contact with the sides of the bases exposed in the major groove.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This situation varies in unusual conformations of DNA within the cell *(see below)*, but the major and minor grooves are always named to reflect the differences in width that would be seen if the DNA was twisted back into the ordinary B form.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Non-covalent hydrogen bonds between the pairs are shown as dashed lines.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In a DNA double helix, each type of nucleobase on one strand bonds with just one type of nucleobase on the other strand.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This is called complementary base pairing.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Purines form hydrogen bonds to pyrimidines, with adenine bonding only to thymine in two hydrogen bonds, and cytosine bonding only to guanine in three hydrogen bonds.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This arrangement of two nucleotides binding together across the double helix (from six-carbon ring to six-carbon ring) is called a Watson-Crick base pair.
[src:dna/dna-p01] DNA with high GC-content is more stable than DNA with low GC-content.
[src:dna/dna-p01] A Hoogsteen base pair (hydrogen bonding the 6-carbon ring to the 5-carbon ring) is a rare variation of base-pairing.
[src:dna/dna-p01] As hydrogen bonds are not covalent, they can be broken and rejoined relatively easily.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The two strands of DNA in a double helix can thus be pulled apart like a zipper, either by a mechanical force or high temperature.
[src:dna/dna-p01] As a result of this base pair complementarity, all the information in the double-stranded sequence of a DNA helix is duplicated on each strand, which is vital in DNA replication.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This reversible and specific interaction between complementary base pairs is critical for all the functions of DNA in organisms.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Most DNA molecules are actually two polymer strands, bound together in a helical fashion by noncovalent bonds; this double-stranded (dsDNA) structure is maintained largely by the intrastrand base stacking interactions, which are strongest for G,C stacks.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The two strands can come apart—a process known as melting—to form two single-stranded DNA (ssDNA) molecules.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Melting occurs at high temperatures, low salt and high pH (low pH also melts DNA, but since DNA is unstable due to acid depurination, low pH is rarely used).
[src:dna/dna-p01] The stability of the dsDNA form depends not only on the GC-content (% G,C basepairs) but also on sequence (since stacking is sequence specific) and also length (longer molecules are more stable).
[src:dna/dna-p01] As a result, it is both the percentage of GC base pairs and the overall length of a DNA double helix that determines the strength of the association between the two strands of DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Long DNA helices with a high GC-content have more strongly interacting strands, while short helices with high AT content have more weakly interacting strands.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In biology, parts of the DNA double helix that need to separate easily, such as the TATAAT Pribnow box in some promoters, tend to have a high AT content, making the strands easier to pull apart.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In the laboratory, the strength of this interaction can be measured by finding the melting temperature *Tm* necessary to break half of the hydrogen bonds.
[src:dna/dna-p01] When all the base pairs in a DNA double helix melt, the strands separate and exist in solution as two entirely independent molecules.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These single-stranded DNA molecules have no single common shape, but some conformations are more stable than others.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In humans, the total female diploid nuclear genome per cell extends for 6.37 Gigabase pairs (Gbp), is 208.23 cm long and weighs 6.51 picograms (pg).
[src:dna/dna-p01] Each DNA polymer can contain hundreds of millions of nucleotides, such as in chromosome 1.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Chromosome 1 is the largest human chromosome with approximately 220 million base pairs, and would be 85 mm long if straightened.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In eukaryotes, in addition to nuclear DNA, there is also mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) which encodes certain proteins used by the mitochondria.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The mtDNA is usually relatively small in comparison to the nuclear DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] For example, the human mitochondrial DNA forms closed circular molecules, each of which contains 16,569 DNA base pairs, with each such molecule normally containing a full set of the mitochondrial genes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Each human mitochondrion contains, on average, approximately 5 such mtDNA molecules.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Each human cell contains approximately 100 mitochondria, giving a total number of mtDNA molecules per human cell of approximately 500.
[src:dna/dna-p01] However, the amount of mitochondria per cell also varies by cell type, and an egg cell can contain 100,000 mitochondria, corresponding to up to 1,500,000 copies of the mitochondrial genome (constituting up to 90% of the DNA of the cell).
[src:dna/dna-p01] A DNA sequence is called a "sense" sequence if it is the same as that of a messenger RNA copy that is translated into protein.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The sequence on the opposite strand is called the "antisense" sequence.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Both sense and antisense sequences can exist on different parts of the same strand of DNA (i.e. both strands can contain both sense and antisense sequences).
[src:dna/dna-p01] In both prokaryotes and eukaryotes, antisense RNA sequences are produced, but the functions of these RNAs are not entirely clear.
[src:dna/dna-p01] One proposal is that antisense RNAs are involved in regulating gene expression through RNA-RNA base pairing.
[src:dna/dna-p01] A few DNA sequences in prokaryotes and eukaryotes, and more in plasmids and viruses, blur the distinction between sense and antisense strands by having overlapping genes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In these cases, some DNA sequences do double duty, encoding one protein when read along one strand, and a second protein when read in the opposite direction along the other strand.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In bacteria, this overlap may be involved in the regulation of gene transcription, while in viruses, overlapping genes increase the amount of information that can be encoded within the small viral genome.
[src:dna/dna-p01] DNA can be twisted like a rope in a process called DNA supercoiling.
[src:dna/dna-p01] With DNA in its "relaxed" state, a strand usually circles the axis of the double helix once every 10.4 base pairs, but if the DNA is twisted the strands become more tightly or more loosely wound.
[src:dna/dna-p01] If the DNA is twisted in the direction of the helix, this is positive supercoiling, and the bases are held more tightly together.
[src:dna/dna-p01] If they are twisted in the opposite direction, this is negative supercoiling, and the bases come apart more easily.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In nature, most DNA has slight negative supercoiling that is introduced by enzymes called topoisomerases.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These enzymes are also needed to relieve the twisting stresses introduced into DNA strands during processes such as transcription and DNA replication.
[src:dna/dna-p01] DNA exists in many possible conformations that include A-DNA, B-DNA, and Z-DNA forms, although only B-DNA and Z-DNA have been directly observed in functional organisms.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The conformation that DNA adopts depends on the hydration level, DNA sequence, the amount and direction of supercoiling, chemical modifications of the bases, the type and concentration of metal ions, and the presence of polyamines in solution.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The first published reports of A-DNA X-ray diffraction patterns—and also B-DNA—used analyses based on Patterson functions that provided only a limited amount of structural information for oriented fibers of DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] An alternative analysis was proposed by Wilkins *et al.* in 1953 for the *in vivo* B-DNA X-ray diffraction-scattering patterns of highly hydrated DNA fibers in terms of squares of Bessel functions.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In the same journal, James Watson and Francis Crick presented their molecular modeling analysis of the DNA X-ray diffraction patterns to suggest that the structure was a double helix.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Although the *B-DNA form* is most common under the conditions found in cells, it is not a well-defined conformation but a family of related DNA conformations that occur at the high hydration levels present in cells.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Their corresponding X-ray diffraction and scattering patterns are characteristic of molecular paracrystals with a significant degree of disorder.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Compared to B-DNA, the A-DNA form is a wider right-handed spiral, with a shallow, wide minor groove and a narrower, deeper major groove.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The A form occurs under non-physiological conditions in partly dehydrated samples of DNA, while in the cell it may be produced in hybrid pairings of DNA and RNA strands, and in enzyme-DNA complexes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Segments of DNA where the bases have been chemically modified by methylation may undergo a larger change in conformation and adopt the Z form.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Here, the strands turn about the helical axis in a left-handed spiral, the opposite of the more common B form.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These unusual structures can be recognized by specific Z-DNA binding proteins and may be involved in the regulation of transcription.
[src:dna/dna-p01] For many years, exobiologists have proposed the existence of a shadow biosphere, a postulated microbial biosphere of Earth that uses radically different biochemical and molecular processes than currently known life.
[src:dna/dna-p01] One of the proposals was the existence of lifeforms that use arsenic instead of phosphorus in DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] A report in 2010 of the possibility in the bacterium GFAJ-1 was announced, though the research was disputed, and evidence suggests the bacterium actively prevents the incorporation of arsenic into the DNA backbone and other biomolecules.
[src:dna/dna-p01] At the ends of the linear chromosomes are specialized regions of DNA called telomeres.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The main function of these regions is to allow the cell to replicate chromosome ends using the enzyme telomerase, as the enzymes that normally replicate DNA cannot copy the extreme 3′ ends of chromosomes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These specialized chromosome caps also help protect the DNA ends, and stop the DNA repair systems in the cell from treating them as damage to be corrected.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In human cells, telomeres are usually lengths of single-stranded DNA containing several thousand repeats of a simple TTAGGG sequence.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These guanine-rich sequences may stabilize chromosome ends by forming structures of stacked sets of four-base units, rather than the usual base pairs found in other DNA molecules.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Here, four guanine bases, known as a guanine tetrad, form a flat plate.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These flat four-base units then stack on top of each other to form a stable G-quadruplex structure.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These structures are stabilized by hydrogen bonding between the edges of the bases and chelation of a metal ion in the centre of each four-base unit.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Other structures can also be formed, with the central set of four bases coming from either a single strand folded around the bases, or several different parallel strands, each contributing one base to the central structure.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In addition to these stacked structures, telomeres also form large loop structures called telomere loops, or T-loops.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Here, the single-stranded DNA curls around in a long circle stabilized by telomere-binding proteins.
[src:dna/dna-p01] At the very end of the T-loop, the single-stranded telomere DNA is held onto a region of double-stranded DNA by the telomere strand disrupting the double-helical DNA and base pairing to one of the two strands.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This triple-stranded structure is called a displacement loop or D-loop.
[src:dna/dna-p01] can form networks containing multiple branches.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In DNA, fraying occurs when non-complementary regions exist at the end of an otherwise complementary double-strand of DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] However, branched DNA can occur if a third strand of DNA is introduced and contains adjoining regions able to hybridize with the frayed regions of the pre-existing double-strand.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Although the simplest example of branched DNA involves only three strands of DNA, complexes involving additional strands and multiple branches are also possible.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Branched DNA can be used in nanotechnology to construct geometric shapes, see the section on uses in technology below.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Several artificial nucleobases have been synthesized, and successfully incorporated in the eight-base DNA analogue named Hachimoji DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Dubbed S, B, P, and Z, these artificial bases are capable of bonding with each other in a predictable way (S–B and P–Z), maintain the double helix structure of DNA, and be transcribed to RNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Their existence could be seen as an indication that there is nothing special about the four natural nucleobases that evolved on Earth.
[src:dna/dna-p01] On the other hand, DNA is tightly related to RNA which does not only act as a transcript of DNA but also performs as molecular machines many tasks in cells.
[src:dna/dna-p01] For this purpose it has to fold into a structure.
[src:dna/dna-p01] It has been shown that to allow to create all possible structures at least four bases are required for the corresponding RNA, while a higher number is also possible but this would be against the natural principle of least effort.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The phosphate groups of DNA give it similar acidic properties to phosphoric acid and it can be considered as a strong acid.
[src:dna/dna-p01] It will be fully ionized at a normal cellular pH, releasing protons which leave behind negative charges on the phosphate groups.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These negative charges protect DNA from breakdown by hydrolysis by repelling nucleophiles which could hydrolyze it.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Pure DNA extracted from cells forms white, stringy clumps.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Structure of cytosine with and without the 5-methyl group.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The expression of genes is influenced by how the DNA is packaged in chromosomes, in a structure called chromatin.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Base modifications can be involved in packaging, with regions that have low or no gene expression usually containing high levels of methylation of cytosine bases.
[src:dna/dna-p01] DNA packaging and its influence on gene expression can also occur by covalent modifications of the histone protein core around which DNA is wrapped in the chromatin structure or else by remodeling carried out by chromatin remodeling complexes (see Chromatin remodeling).
[src:dna/dna-p01] There is, further, crosstalk between DNA methylation and histone modification, so they can coordinately affect chromatin and gene expression.
[src:dna/dna-p01] For one example, cytosine methylation produces 5-methylcytosine, which is important for X-inactivation of chromosomes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The average level of methylation varies between organisms—the worm *Caenorhabditis elegans* lacks cytosine methylation, while vertebrates have higher levels, with up to 1% of their DNA containing 5-methylcytosine.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Despite the importance of 5-methylcytosine, it can deaminate to leave a thymine base, so methylated cytosines are particularly prone to mutations.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Other base modifications include adenine methylation in bacteria, the presence of 5-hydroxymethylcytosine in the brain, and the glycosylation of uracil to produce the "J-base" in kinetoplastids.
[src:dna/dna-p01] DNA can be damaged by many sorts of mutagens, which change the DNA sequence.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Mutagens include oxidizing agents, alkylating agents and also high-energy electromagnetic radiation such as ultraviolet light and X-rays.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The type of DNA damage produced depends on the type of mutagen.
[src:dna/dna-p01] For example, UV light can damage DNA by producing thymine dimers, which are cross-links between pyrimidine bases.
[src:dna/dna-p01] On the other hand, oxidants such as free radicals or hydrogen peroxide produce multiple forms of damage, including base modifications, particularly of guanosine, and double-strand breaks.
[src:dna/dna-p01] A typical human cell contains about 150,000 bases that have suffered oxidative damage.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Of these oxidative lesions, the most dangerous are double-strand breaks, as these are difficult to repair and can produce point mutations, insertions, deletions from the DNA sequence, and chromosomal translocations.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Because of inherent limits in the DNA repair mechanisms, if humans lived long enough, they would all eventually develop cancer.
[src:dna/dna-p01] DNA damages that are naturally occurring, due to normal cellular processes that produce reactive oxygen species, the hydrolytic activities of cellular water, etc., also occur frequently.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Although most of these damages are repaired, in any cell some DNA damage may remain despite the action of repair processes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These remaining DNA damages accumulate with age in mammalian postmitotic tissues.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This accumulation appears to be an important underlying cause of aging.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Many mutagens fit into the space between two adjacent base pairs, this is called *intercalation*.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Most intercalators are aromatic and planar molecules; examples include ethidium bromide, acridines, daunomycin, and doxorubicin.
[src:dna/dna-p01] For an intercalator to fit between base pairs, the bases must separate, distorting the DNA strands by unwinding of the double helix.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This inhibits both transcription and DNA replication, causing toxicity and mutations.
[src:dna/dna-p01] As a result, DNA intercalators may be carcinogens, and in the case of thalidomide, a teratogen.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Others such as benzo[*a*]pyrene diol epoxide and aflatoxin form DNA adducts that induce errors in replication.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Nevertheless, due to their ability to inhibit DNA transcription and replication, other similar toxins are also used in chemotherapy to inhibit rapidly growing cancer cells.
[src:dna/dna-p01] DNA usually occurs as linear chromosomes in eukaryotes, and circular chromosomes in prokaryotes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The set of chromosomes in a cell makes up its genome; the human genome has approximately 3 billion base pairs of DNA arranged into 46 chromosomes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The information carried by DNA is held in the sequence of pieces of DNA called genes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Transmission of genetic information in genes is achieved via complementary base pairing.
[src:dna/dna-p01] For example, in transcription, when a cell uses the information in a gene, the DNA sequence is copied into a complementary RNA sequence through the attraction between the DNA and the correct RNA nucleotides.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Usually, this RNA copy is then used to make a matching protein sequence in a process called translation, which depends on the same interaction between RNA nucleotides.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In an alternative fashion, a cell may copy its genetic information in a process called DNA replication.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The details of these functions are covered in other articles; here the focus is on the interactions between DNA and other molecules that mediate the function of the genome.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Genomic DNA is tightly and orderly packed in the process called DNA condensation, to fit the small available volumes of the cell.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In eukaryotes, DNA is located in the cell nucleus, with small amounts in mitochondria and chloroplasts.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In prokaryotes, the DNA is held within an irregularly shaped body in the cytoplasm called the nucleoid.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The functional genetic information in a genome is located in genes, regulatory sequences, origins of replication, centromeres, telomeres, and segments required for the three-dimensional structure of chromatin.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In many complex eukaryotes, only a small fraction of the total sequence is devoted to the various functional elements.
[src:dna/dna-p01] For example, in humans less than 10% of the genome has a defined functional role and the rest (90%) is probably junk DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] A gene is a sequence of DNA that contains genetic information and can influence the phenotype of an organism.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Within a gene, the sequence of bases along a DNA strand defines a messenger RNA sequence, which then defines one or more protein sequences.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The relationship between the nucleotide sequences of genes and the amino-acid sequences of proteins is determined by the rules of translation, known collectively as the genetic code.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The genetic code consists of three-letter 'words' called *codons* formed from a sequence of three nucleotides (e.g., ACT, CAG, TTT).
[src:dna/dna-p01] In transcription, the codons of a gene are copied into messenger RNA by RNA polymerase.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This RNA copy is then decoded by a ribosome that reads the RNA sequence by base-pairing the messenger RNA to transfer RNA, which carries amino acids.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Since there are 4 bases in 3-letter combinations, there are 64 possible codons (43 combinations).
[src:dna/dna-p01] These encode the twenty standard amino acids, giving most amino acids more than one possible codon.
[src:dna/dna-p01] There are also three 'stop' or 'nonsense' codons signifying the end of the coding region; these are the TAG, TAA, and TGA codons, (UAG, UAA, and UGA on the mRNA).
[src:dna/dna-p01] Cell division is essential for an organism to grow, but, when a cell divides, it must replicate the DNA in its genome so that the two daughter cells have the same genetic information as their parent.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The double-stranded structure of DNA provides a simple mechanism for DNA replication.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Here, the two strands are separated and then each strand's complementary DNA sequence is recreated by an enzyme called DNA polymerase.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This enzyme makes the complementary strand by finding the correct base through complementary base pairing and bonding it onto the original strand.
[src:dna/dna-p01] As DNA polymerases can only extend a DNA strand in a 5′ to 3′ direction, different mechanisms are used to copy the antiparallel strands of the double helix.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In this way, the base on the old strand dictates which base appears on the new strand, and the cell ends up with a perfect copy of its DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Naked extracellular DNA (eDNA), most of it released by cell death, is nearly ubiquitous in the environment.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Its concentration in soil may be as high as 2 μg/L, and its concentration in natural aquatic environments may be as high at 88 μg/L.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Various possible functions have been proposed for eDNA: it may be involved in horizontal gene transfer; it may provide nutrients; and it may act as a buffer to recruit or titrate ions or antibiotics.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Extracellular DNA acts as a functional extracellular matrix component in the biofilms of several bacterial species.
[src:dna/dna-p01] It may act as a recognition factor to regulate the attachment and dispersal of specific cell types in the biofilm; it may contribute to biofilm formation; and it may contribute to the biofilm's physical strength and resistance to biological stress.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Cell-free fetal DNA is found in the blood of the mother, and can be sequenced to determine a great deal of information about the developing fetus.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Under the name of environmental DNA eDNA has seen increased use in the natural sciences as a survey tool for ecology, monitoring the movements and presence of species in water, air, or on land, and assessing an area's biodiversity.
[src:dna/dna-p01] All the functions of DNA depend on interactions with proteins.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These protein interactions can be non-specific, or the protein can bind specifically to a single DNA sequence.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Enzymes can also bind to DNA and of these, the polymerases that copy the DNA base sequence in transcription and DNA replication are particularly important.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Structural proteins that bind DNA are well-understood examples of non-specific DNA-protein interactions.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Within chromosomes, DNA is held in complexes with structural proteins.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These proteins organize the DNA into a compact structure called chromatin.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In eukaryotes, this structure involves DNA binding to a complex of small basic proteins called histones, while in prokaryotes multiple types of proteins are involved.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The histones form a disk-shaped complex called a nucleosome, which contains two complete turns of double-stranded DNA wrapped around its surface.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These non-specific interactions are formed through basic residues in the histones, making ionic bonds to the acidic sugar-phosphate backbone of the DNA, and are thus largely independent of the base sequence.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Chemical modifications of these basic amino acid residues include methylation, phosphorylation, and acetylation.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These chemical changes alter the strength of the interaction between the DNA and the histones, making the DNA more or less accessible to transcription factors and changing the rate of transcription.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Other non-specific DNA-binding proteins in chromatin include the high-mobility group proteins, which bind to bent or distorted DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These proteins are important in bending arrays of nucleosomes and arranging them into the larger structures that make up chromosomes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] A distinct group of DNA-binding proteins is the DNA-binding proteins that specifically bind single-stranded DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In humans, replication protein A is the best-understood member of this family and is used in processes where the double helix is separated, including DNA replication, recombination, and DNA repair.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These binding proteins seem to stabilize single-stranded DNA and protect it from forming stem-loops or being degraded by nucleases.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In contrast, other proteins have evolved to bind to particular DNA sequences.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The most intensively studied of these are the various transcription factors, which are proteins that regulate transcription.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Each transcription factor binds to one particular set of DNA sequences and activates or inhibits the transcription of genes that have these sequences close to their promoters.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The transcription factors do this in two ways.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Firstly, they can bind the RNA polymerase responsible for transcription, either directly or through other mediator proteins; this locates the polymerase at the promoter and allows it to begin transcription.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Alternatively, transcription factors can bind enzymes that modify the histones at the promoter.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This changes the accessibility of the DNA template to the polymerase.
[src:dna/dna-p01] As these DNA targets can occur throughout an organism's genome, changes in the activity of one type of transcription factor can affect thousands of genes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Consequently, these proteins are often the targets of the signal transduction processes that control responses to environmental changes or cellular differentiation and development.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The specificity of these transcription factors' interactions with DNA come from the proteins making multiple contacts to the edges of the DNA bases, allowing them to "read" the DNA sequence.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Most of these base-interactions are made in the major groove, where the bases are most accessible.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Nucleases are enzymes that cut DNA strands by catalyzing the hydrolysis of the phosphodiester bonds.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Nucleases that hydrolyse nucleotides from the ends of DNA strands are called exonucleases, while endonucleases cut within strands.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The most frequently used nucleases in molecular biology are the restriction endonucleases, which cut DNA at specific sequences.
[src:dna/dna-p01] For instance, the EcoRV enzyme shown to the left recognizes the 6-base sequence 5′-GATATC-3′ and makes a cut at the horizontal line.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In nature, these enzymes protect bacteria against phage infection by digesting the phage DNA when it enters the bacterial cell, acting as part of the restriction modification system.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In technology, these sequence-specific nucleases are used in molecular cloning and DNA fingerprinting.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Enzymes called DNA ligases can rejoin cut or broken DNA strands.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Ligases are particularly important in lagging strand DNA replication, as they join the short segments of DNA produced at the replication fork into a complete copy of the DNA template.
[src:dna/dna-p01] They are also used in DNA repair and genetic recombination.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Topoisomerases are enzymes with both nuclease and ligase activity.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These proteins change the amount of supercoiling in DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Some of these enzymes work by cutting the DNA helix and allowing one section to rotate, thereby reducing its level of supercoiling; the enzyme then seals the DNA break.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Other types of these enzymes are capable of cutting one DNA helix and then passing a second strand of DNA through this break, before rejoining the helix.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Topoisomerases are required for many processes involving DNA, such as DNA replication and transcription.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Helicases are proteins that are a type of molecular motor.
[src:dna/dna-p01] They use the chemical energy in nucleoside triphosphates, predominantly adenosine triphosphate (ATP), to break hydrogen bonds between bases and unwind the DNA double helix into single strands.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These enzymes are essential for most processes where enzymes need to access the DNA bases.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Polymerases are enzymes that synthesize polynucleotide chains from nucleoside triphosphates.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The sequence of their products is created based on existing polynucleotide chains—which are called *templates*.
[src:dna/dna-p01] These enzymes function by repeatedly adding a nucleotide to the 3′ hydroxyl group at the end of the growing polynucleotide chain.
[src:dna/dna-p01] As a consequence, all polymerases work in a 5′ to 3′ direction.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In the active site of these enzymes, the incoming nucleoside triphosphate base-pairs to the template: this allows polymerases to accurately synthesize the complementary strand of their template.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Polymerases are classified according to the type of template that they use.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In DNA replication, DNA-dependent DNA polymerases make copies of DNA polynucleotide chains.
[src:dna/dna-p01] To preserve biological information, it is essential that the sequence of bases in each copy are precisely complementary to the sequence of bases in the template strand.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Many DNA polymerases have a proofreading activity.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Here, the polymerase recognizes the occasional mistakes in the synthesis reaction by the lack of base pairing between the mismatched nucleotides.
[src:dna/dna-p01] If a mismatch is detected, a 3′ to 5′ exonuclease activity is activated and the incorrect base removed.
[src:dna/dna-p01] In most organisms, DNA polymerases function in a large complex called the replisome that contains multiple accessory subunits, such as the DNA clamp or helicases.
[src:dna/dna-p01] RNA-dependent DNA polymerases are a specialized class of polymerases that copy the sequence of an RNA strand into DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] They include reverse transcriptase, which is a viral enzyme involved in the infection of cells by retroviruses, and telomerase, which is required for the replication of telomeres.
[src:dna/dna-p01] For example, HIV reverse transcriptase is an enzyme for AIDS virus replication.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Telomerase is an unusual polymerase because it contains its own RNA template as part of its structure.
[src:dna/dna-p01] It synthesizes telomeres at the ends of chromosomes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Telomeres prevent fusion of the ends of neighboring chromosomes and protect chromosome ends from damage.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Transcription is carried out by a DNA-dependent RNA polymerase that copies the sequence of a DNA strand into RNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] To begin transcribing a gene, the RNA polymerase binds to a sequence of DNA called a promoter and separates the DNA strands.
[src:dna/dna-p01] It then copies the gene sequence into a messenger RNA transcript until it reaches a region of DNA called the terminator, where it halts and detaches from the DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] As with human DNA-dependent DNA polymerases, RNA polymerase II, the enzyme that transcribes most of the genes in the human genome, operates as part of a large protein complex with multiple regulatory and accessory subunits.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The four separate DNA strands are coloured red, blue, green and yellow.
[src:dna/dna-p01] A DNA helix usually does not interact with other segments of DNA, and in human cells, the different chromosomes even occupy separate areas in the nucleus called "chromosome territories".
[src:dna/dna-p01] This physical separation of different chromosomes is important for the ability of DNA to function as a stable repository for information, as one of the few times chromosomes interact is in chromosomal crossover which occurs during sexual reproduction, when genetic recombination occurs.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Chromosomal crossover is when two DNA helices break, swap a section and then rejoin.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Recombination allows chromosomes to exchange genetic information and produces new combinations of genes, which increases the efficiency of natural selection and can be important in the rapid evolution of new proteins.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Genetic recombination can also be involved in DNA repair, particularly in the cell's response to double-strand breaks.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The most common form of chromosomal crossover is homologous recombination, where the two chromosomes involved share very similar sequences.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Non-homologous recombination can be damaging to cells, as it can produce chromosomal translocations and genetic abnormalities.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The recombination reaction is catalyzed by enzymes known as recombinases, such as RAD51.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The first step in recombination is a double-stranded break caused by either an endonuclease or damage to the DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] A series of steps catalyzed in part by the recombinase then leads to joining of the two helices by at least one Holliday junction, in which a segment of a single strand in each helix is annealed to the complementary strand in the other helix.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The Holliday junction is a tetrahedral junction structure that can be moved along the pair of chromosomes, swapping one strand for another.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The recombination reaction is then halted by cleavage of the junction and re-ligation of the released DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Only strands of like polarity exchange DNA during recombination.
[src:dna/dna-p01] There are two types of cleavage: east-west cleavage and north–south cleavage.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The north–south cleavage nicks both strands of DNA, while the east–west cleavage has one strand of DNA intact.
[src:dna/dna-p01] The formation of a Holliday junction during recombination makes it possible for genetic diversity, genes to exchange on chromosomes, and expression of wild-type viral genomes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] DNA contains the genetic information that allows all forms of life to function, grow and reproduce.
[src:dna/dna-p01] However, it is unclear how long in the 4-billion-year history of life DNA has performed this function, as it has been proposed that the earliest forms of life may have used RNA as their genetic material.
[src:dna/dna-p01] RNA may have acted as the central part of early cell metabolism as it can both transmit genetic information and carry out catalysis as part of ribozymes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This ancient RNA world where nucleic acid would have been used for both catalysis and genetics may have influenced the evolution of the current genetic code based on four nucleotide bases.
[src:dna/dna-p01] This would occur, since the number of different bases in such an organism is a trade-off between a small number of bases increasing replication accuracy and a large number of bases increasing the catalytic efficiency of ribozymes.
[src:dna/dna-p01] However, there is no direct evidence of ancient genetic systems, as recovery of DNA from most fossils is impossible because DNA survives in the environment for less than one million years, and slowly degrades into short fragments in solution.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Claims for older DNA have been made, most notably a report of the isolation of a viable bacterium from a salt crystal 250 million years old, but these claims are controversial.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Building blocks of DNA (adenine, guanine, and related organic molecules) may have been formed extraterrestrially in outer space.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Complex DNA and RNA organic compounds of life, including uracil, cytosine, and thymine, have also been formed in the laboratory under conditions mimicking those found in outer space, using starting chemicals, such as pyrimidine, found in meteorites.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Pyrimidine, like polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs), the most carbon-rich chemical found in the universe, may have been formed in red giants or in interstellar cosmic dust and gas clouds.
[src:dna/dna-p01] Ancient DNA has been recovered from ancient organisms at a timescale where genome evolution can be directly observed, including from extinct organisms up to millions of years old, such as the woolly mammoth.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Methods have been developed to purify DNA from organisms, such as phenol-chloroform extraction, and to manipulate it in the laboratory, such as restriction digests and the polymerase chain reaction.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Modern biology and biochemistry make intensive use of these techniques in recombinant DNA technology.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Recombinant DNA is a man-made DNA sequence that has been assembled from other DNA sequences.
[src:dna/dna-p02] They can be transformed into organisms in the form of plasmids or in the appropriate format, by using a viral vector.
[src:dna/dna-p02] The genetically modified organisms produced can be used to produce products such as recombinant proteins, used in medical research, or be grown in agriculture.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Forensic scientists can use DNA in blood, semen, skin, saliva or hair found at a crime scene to identify a matching DNA of an individual, such as a perpetrator.
[src:dna/dna-p02] This process is formally termed DNA profiling, also called *DNA fingerprinting*.
[src:dna/dna-p02] In DNA profiling, the lengths of variable sections of repetitive DNA, such as short tandem repeats and minisatellites, are compared between people.
[src:dna/dna-p02] This method is usually an extremely reliable technique for identifying a matching DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p02] However, identification can be complicated if the scene is contaminated with DNA from several people.
[src:dna/dna-p02] DNA profiling was developed in 1984 by British geneticist Sir Alec Jeffreys, and first used in forensic science to convict Colin Pitchfork in the 1988 Enderby murders case.
[src:dna/dna-p02] The development of forensic science and the ability to now obtain genetic matching on minute samples of blood, skin, saliva, or hair has led to re-examining many cases.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Evidence can now be uncovered that was scientifically impossible at the time of the original examination.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Combined with the removal of the double jeopardy law in some places, this can allow cases to be reopened where prior trials have failed to produce sufficient evidence to convince a jury.
[src:dna/dna-p02] People charged with serious crimes may be required to provide a sample of DNA for matching purposes.
[src:dna/dna-p02] The most obvious defense to DNA matches obtained forensically is to claim that cross-contamination of evidence has occurred.
[src:dna/dna-p02] This has resulted in meticulous strict handling procedures with new cases of serious crime.
[src:dna/dna-p02] DNA profiling is also used successfully to positively identify victims of mass casualty incidents, bodies or body parts in serious accidents, and individual victims in mass war graves, via matching to family members.
[src:dna/dna-p02] DNA profiling is also used in DNA paternity testing to determine if someone is the biological parent or grandparent of a child with the probability of parentage is typically 99.99% when the alleged parent is biologically related to the child.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Usually DNA sequencing are carried out after birth, but there are new methods to test paternity while a mother is still pregnant.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Deoxyribozymes, also called DNAzymes or catalytic DNA, were first discovered in 1994.
[src:dna/dna-p02] They are mostly single stranded DNA sequences isolated from a large pool of random DNA sequences through a combinatorial approach called in vitro selection or systematic evolution of ligands by exponential enrichment (SELEX).
[src:dna/dna-p02] DNAzymes catalyze variety of chemical reactions including RNA-DNA cleavage, RNA-DNA ligation, amino acids phosphorylation-dephosphorylation, carbon-carbon bond formation, etc.
[src:dna/dna-p02] DNAzymes can enhance catalytic rate of chemical reactions up to 100,000,000,000-fold over the uncatalyzed reaction.
[src:dna/dna-p02] The most extensively studied class of DNAzymes is RNA-cleaving types which have been used to detect different metal ions and designing therapeutic agents.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Several metal-specific DNAzymes have been reported including the GR-5 DNAzyme (lead-specific), the CA1-3 DNAzymes (copper-specific), the 39E DNAzyme (uranyl-specific) and the NaA43 DNAzyme (sodium-specific).
[src:dna/dna-p02] The NaA43 DNAzyme, which is reported to be more than 10,000-fold selective for sodium over other metal ions, was used to make a real-time sodium sensor in cells.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Bioinformatics involves the development of techniques to store, data mine, search and manipulate biological data, including DNA nucleic acid sequence data.
[src:dna/dna-p02] These have led to widely applied advances in computer science, especially string searching algorithms, machine learning, and database theory.
[src:dna/dna-p02] String searching or matching algorithms, which find an occurrence of a sequence of letters inside a larger sequence of letters, were developed to search for specific sequences of nucleotides.
[src:dna/dna-p02] The DNA sequence may be aligned with other DNA sequences to identify homologous sequences and locate the specific mutations that make them distinct.
[src:dna/dna-p02] These techniques, especially multiple sequence alignment, are used in studying phylogenetic relationships and protein function.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Data sets representing entire genomes' worth of DNA sequences, such as those produced by the Human Genome Project, are difficult to use without the annotations that identify the locations of genes and regulatory elements on each chromosome.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Entire genomes may also be compared, which can shed light on the evolutionary history of particular organism and permit the examination of complex evolutionary events.
[src:dna/dna-p02] DNA nanotechnology uses the unique molecular recognition properties of DNA and other nucleic acids to create self-assembling branched DNA complexes with useful properties.
[src:dna/dna-p02] DNA is thus used as a structural material rather than as a carrier of biological information.
[src:dna/dna-p02] This has led to the creation of two-dimensional periodic lattices (both tile-based and using the *DNA origami* method) and three-dimensional structures in the shapes of polyhedra.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Nanomechanical devices and algorithmic self-assembly have also been demonstrated, and these DNA structures have been used to template the arrangement of other molecules such as gold nanoparticles and streptavidin proteins.
[src:dna/dna-p02] DNA and other nucleic acids are the basis of aptamers, synthetic oligonucleotide ligands for specific target molecules used in a range of biotechnology and biomedical applications.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Because DNA collects mutations over time, which are then inherited, it contains historical information, and, by comparing DNA sequences, geneticists can infer the evolutionary history of organisms, their phylogeny.
[src:dna/dna-p02] This field of phylogenetics is a powerful tool in evolutionary biology.
[src:dna/dna-p02] If DNA sequences within a species are compared, population geneticists can learn the history of particular populations.
[src:dna/dna-p02] This can be used in studies ranging from ecological genetics to anthropology.
[src:dna/dna-p02] DNA as a storage device for information has enormous potential since it has much higher storage density compared to electronic devices.
[src:dna/dna-p02] However, high costs, slow read and write times (memory latency), and insufficient reliability has prevented its practical use.
[src:dna/dna-p02] DNA was first isolated by the Swiss physician Friedrich Miescher who, in 1869, discovered a microscopic substance in the pus of discarded surgical bandages.
[src:dna/dna-p02] As it resided in the nuclei of cells, he called it "nuclein".
[src:dna/dna-p02] In 1878, Albrecht Kossel isolated the non-protein component of "nuclein", nucleic acid, and later isolated its five primary nucleobases.
[src:dna/dna-p02] In 1909, Phoebus Levene identified the base, sugar, and phosphate nucleotide unit of RNA (then named "yeast nucleic acid").
[src:dna/dna-p02] In 1929, Levene identified deoxyribose sugar in "thymus nucleic acid" (DNA).
[src:dna/dna-p02] Levene suggested that DNA consisted of a string of four nucleotide units linked together through the phosphate groups ("Tetranucleotide hypothesis").
[src:dna/dna-p02] Levene thought the chain was short and the bases repeated in a fixed order.
[src:dna/dna-p02] In 1927, Nikolai Koltsov proposed that inherited traits would be inherited via a "giant hereditary molecule" made up of "two mirror strands that would replicate in a semi-conservative fashion using each strand as a template".
[src:dna/dna-p02] In 1928, Frederick Griffith in his experiment discovered that traits of the "smooth" form of *Pneumococcus* could be transferred to the "rough" form of the same bacteria by mixing killed "smooth" bacteria with the live "rough" form.
[src:dna/dna-p02] This system provided the first clear suggestion that DNA carries genetic information.
[src:dna/dna-p02] In 1933, while studying virgin sea urchin eggs, Jean Brachet suggested that DNA is found in the cell nucleus and that RNA is present exclusively in the cytoplasm.
[src:dna/dna-p02] At the time, "yeast nucleic acid" (RNA) was thought to occur only in plants, while "thymus nucleic acid" (DNA) only in animals.
[src:dna/dna-p02] The latter was thought to be a tetramer, with the function of buffering cellular pH.
[src:dna/dna-p02] In 1937, William Astbury produced the first X-ray diffraction patterns that showed that DNA had a regular structure.
[src:dna/dna-p02] In 1943, Oswald Avery, along with co-workers Colin MacLeod and Maclyn McCarty, identified DNA as the transforming principle, supporting Griffith's suggestion (Avery–MacLeod–McCarty experiment).
[src:dna/dna-p02] Erwin Chargaff developed and published observations now known as Chargaff's rules, stating that in DNA from any species of any organism, the amount of guanine should be equal to cytosine and the amount of adenine should be equal to thymine.
[src:dna/dna-p02] By 1951, Alec Todd and collaborators at the University of Cambridge had determined by biochemical methods how the backbone of DNA is structured via the successive linking of carbon atoms 3 and 5 of the sugar to phosphates.
[src:dna/dna-p02] This would help to corroborate Watson and Crick's later X-ray structural work.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Todd would later be awarded the 1957 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for this and other discoveries related to DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Late in 1951, Francis Crick started working with James Watson at the Cavendish Laboratory within the University of Cambridge.
[src:dna/dna-p02] DNA's role in heredity was confirmed in 1952 when Alfred Hershey and Martha Chase in the Hershey–Chase experiment showed that DNA is the genetic material of the enterobacteria phage T2.
[src:dna/dna-p02] In May 1952, Raymond Gosling, a graduate student working under the supervision of Rosalind Franklin, took an X-ray diffraction image, labeled as "Photo 51", at high hydration levels of DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p02] This photo was given to Watson and Crick by Maurice Wilkins and was critical to their obtaining the correct structure of DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Franklin told Crick and Watson that the backbones had to be on the outside.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Before then, Linus Pauling, and Watson and Crick, had erroneous models with the chains inside and the bases pointing outwards.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Franklin's identification of the space group for DNA crystals proved her correct.
[src:dna/dna-p02] In February 1953, Linus Pauling and Robert Corey proposed a model for nucleic acids containing three intertwined chains, with the phosphates near the axis, and the bases on the outside.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Watson and Crick completed their model, which is now accepted as the first correct model of the double helix of DNA.
[src:dna/dna-p02] On 28 February 1953 Crick interrupted patrons' lunchtime at The Eagle pub in Cambridge, England to announce that he and Watson had "discovered the secret of life".
[src:dna/dna-p02] The 25 April 1953 issue of the journal *Nature* published a series of five articles giving the Watson and Crick double-helix structure DNA and evidence supporting it.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Then followed a letter by Wilkins and two of his colleagues, which contained an analysis of *in vivo* B-DNA X-ray patterns, and which supported the presence *in vivo* of the Watson and Crick structure.
[src:dna/dna-p02] In April 2023, scientists, based on new evidence, concluded that Rosalind Franklin was a contributor and "equal player" in the discovery process of DNA, rather than otherwise, as may have been presented subsequently after the time of the discovery.
[src:dna/dna-p02] In 1962, after Franklin's death, Watson, Crick, and Wilkins jointly received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Nobel Prizes are awarded only to living recipients.
[src:dna/dna-p02] A debate continues about who should receive credit for the discovery.
[src:dna/dna-p02] In an influential presentation in 1957, Crick laid out the central dogma of molecular biology, which foretold the relationship between DNA, RNA, and proteins, and articulated the "adaptor hypothesis".
[src:dna/dna-p02] Final confirmation of the replication mechanism that was implied by the double-helical structure followed in 1958 through the Meselson–Stahl experiment.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Further work by Crick and co-workers showed that the genetic code was based on non-overlapping triplets of bases, called codons, allowing Har Gobind Khorana, Robert W.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Holley, and Marshall Warren Nirenberg to decipher the genetic code.
[src:dna/dna-p02] These findings represent the birth of molecular biology.
[src:dna/dna-p02] In 1986, DNA analysis was first used in a criminal investigation when police in the UK requested Alec Jeffreys of the University of Leicester to prove or disprove the involvement in a particular case of a suspect who claimed innocence in the matter.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Although the suspect had already confessed to committing a recent rape-murder, he was denying any involvement in a similar crime committed three years earlier.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Yet the details of the two cases were so alike that the police concluded both crimes had been committed by the same person.
[src:dna/dna-p02] However, all charges against the suspect were dropped when Jeffreys' DNA testing exonerated the suspect — from both the earlier murder and the one to which he'd confessed.
[src:dna/dna-p02] Further such DNA profiling led to positive identification of another suspect (Colin Pitchfork) who, in 1988, was found guilty of both rape-murders.
